INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,3,3,'und',0,'<h1>Our Research</h1>\r\n\r\n<p><center><h3>Case-control Study</h3></center></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The MelaNostrum case-control study consists of melanoma patients recruited from hospitals, universities, and clinical centers affiliated with consortium members from Italy, Spain, Greece, and Cyprus, along with controls recruited at each site. Clinical and phenotypic information, such as number of melanocytic nevi (moles) and freckles, skin type, hair and eye color, and sunburns, as well as environmental exposures were collected by clinical examination, interviews, and/or self-report. Data and biospecimens collected from participants of this study will be used to investigate melanoma risk and progression associated with genetic, phenotypic, and environmental factors. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em>Case-control study projects:</em></strong><p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Genome-wide association study (GWAS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Maria Teresa Landi</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have identified several genetic variants, mainly in proximity of genes that are related to pigmentation, nevus (mole) density, DNA repair or telomere maintenance, that are associated with melanoma risk. GWAS studies of melanoma risk, however, have included few individuals of Mediterranean descent. This case-control study will compare genetic variants among melanoma patients from Mediterranean countries to healthy people from the general populations of those countries and then combine the results with results from other populations to investigate the common and different pathways leading to melanoma development.  </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Next generation sequencing for characterization of non-acral sporadic cutaneous melanoma unrelated to common risk factors</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Eduardo Nagore</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most cutaneous melanomas develop through patterns of either:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>sun sensitivity (i.e. fair pigmentation of skin and hair) and chronic sun damage, or </li>\r\n <li>melanocytic nevi (moles) and intermittent sun exposure. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>However, a small percentage of non-acral melanomas are unrelated to common known risk factors. It is thought these non-acral melanomas are associated with susceptibility genes unrelated to pigmentation or nevi-proneness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The goals of this study are to:\r\n\r\n<ol type=\"1\">\r\n <li>Identify and characterize non-acral melanomas that are not associated to chronic sun damage, nevi-proneness or other common risk factors, and </li>\r\n <li>Understand if these melanomas have distinct clinical behaviors and prognoses.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Targeted sequencing will be performed on DNA extracted from tumors of patients with and without common risk factors. The results will be used to classify melanomas based on specific mutation profiles and to compare survival between different disease types. The findings can be of great clinical importance because melanomas that develop in the absence of common risk factors tend to be asymptomatic and occur at young ages. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Analysis of phenotypic characteristics, sun exposure, and genetic variants in Southern Europe, Northern Europe, and Australia</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Maria Teresa Landi</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Melanocytic nevus (mole) count has a strong genetic component. For individuals with many nevi, melanoma risk is only moderately associated with sun exposure. Alternatively, melanoma risk among individuals with few or no nevi is strongly associated with patterns of sun exposure. Complicating these risk patterns are pigmentation phenotypes (fair vs. dark), which also have strong genetic components. Pigmentation is associated with sun sensitivity and may also influence an individual\'s sun exposure behaviors. In this study three populations that differ in pigmentation and sun intensity: Southern Europe (dark pigmentation, intense sun), Northern Europe (fair pigmentation, moderate sun), and Australia (fair pigmentation, intense sun), will be investigated to better understand the complex patterns of association between phenotypic characteristics, genetic variants, and melanoma risk. Sun exposure intensity and pattern has been assessed via self-report and/or satellite measurement of UVA/UVB radiation and measurement of chronic sun damage in the area adjacent to melanoma lesions. Additional molecular and genomics analyses will be conducted in the future. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Imputation of HLA-region and association with melanoma risk and response to treatment</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Maria Teresa Landi</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The HLA system (human leukocyte antigen) plays an essential role in immune system function. Proteins in one part of this system display peptides from inside a cell onto the surface of the cell where they can be identified by T-cells of the immune system. T-cells recognize and bind to foreign or non-self peptides, which initiates a process that causes cell death. The role of HLA in the recognition of abnormal cells by the immune system may be important for cancer risk and treatment. In this study, the HLA gene region will be genotyped and imputed or directly sequenced from DNA extracted from the healthy tissue of melanoma patients that have undergone immunotherapy. HLA data will be used to investigate possible associations between HLA variants and responses to immunotherapy, which includes: survival, melanoma progression, changes in tumor size, metastasis, and recurrences. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><center><h3>Family Study</h3></center></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Individuals with two or more 1st degree relatives with a history of melanoma are at greater risk of developing melanoma than the general population. Only a portion of these familial melanomas are attributable to the heritable genetic risks that have been identified to-date or risk factors shared among close relatives such as pigmentation and sun exposure patterns. The MelaNostrum Family Study seeks to further understand familial melanoma risk by incorporating sequencing data from Mediterranean/Southern European, Northern European and Australian populations - offering an opportunity to study familial melanoma risk across different populations. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em>Family study projects: </em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Whole exome sequencing to identify rare or rare and common variants and melanoma risk in familial settings</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Maria Teresa Landi</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A portion of familial melanoma risk is hereditary in nature. A few susceptibility genes have already been identified, including CDKN2A and CDK4 - both of which have a role in cell cycle progression. Collaborative research involving members of MelaNostrum have recently identified a rare variant in the Protection of Telomeres 1 (POT1) as a high susceptibility gene. The variant arose as a founder mutation in the area of Romagna, Italy. Whole-exome sequencing - sequencing of the protein coding regions of DNA - in melanoma-prone families, excluding those with known mutations such as CDKN2A and CDK4, will be performed to continue investigating rare and/or common genetic variants associated with melanoma risk in a familial setting. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Effects of immunity on the development of melanoma in families where genetic and environmental factors are similar</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Maria Teresa Landi</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There tends to be a high degree of similarity among family members with respect to common, known melanoma risk factors, including skin type and sun exposure patterns. This presents an opportunity to investigate how variation in other factors, such as immunity, may affect the development of melanoma. Associations between melanoma development and immunological markers measured in blood will be investigated. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ATM mutations in melanoma susceptibility</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Paola Ghiorzo</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>ATM is a gene that plays an important role in DNA repair. Consequently, ATM is associated with predisposition to certain cancers. Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have established ATM as a low penetrance melanoma susceptibility gene and population studies have linked specific ATM genetic variants with increased melanoma risk. To better understand the role of ATM in melanoma susceptibility, this study will evaluate ATM gene variants observed in melanoma-prone families. ATM data will be collected from melanoma-prone families, unrelated melanoma patients, and disease-free individuals. The number of loss of function (inactivation) and missense (amino acid substitution) ATM variants in melanoma-prone family members and melanoma patients will be identified and compared to disease-free controls.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Evaluation of CCDC83 as a candidate melanoma susceptibility gene</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Susana Puig</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CCDC83 gene has been found to be expressed to a much higher degree in several cancers than in normal healthy tissue. Mutations of CCDC83 have also been observed in several tumors, including melanomas. Although the specific function of the gene has not been well established, genome analyses of melanoma-prone families have identified variants of CCDC83 as one of the likely discriminators between family members that develop melanoma and those that do not. These observations provide a rationale for assessing the possible role of CCDC83 in melanoma susceptibility. This study will investigate the association between CCDC83 and melanoma by comparing the prevalence of loss of function (inactivation) and missense (amino acid substitution) CCDC83 variants identified in melanoma-prone families to families not prone to developing melanoma. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Evaluation of SLC45A2 variant rs250417 and MC1R variants as modifying factors for the development of melanoma in CDKN2A mutation carriers from Mediterranean countries</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Susana Puig</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fair skin and hair, and sun sensitivity are known risk factors for melanoma development. The master regulator of pigmentation is the gene melanocortin-1 receptor (MC1R). When activated it leads to the production of eumelanin - brown/black/dark pigmentation. The gene SLC45A2 also influences pigmentation by playing a role in melanin synthesis. Genetic variations in both these genes have been linked to increased risk of melanoma. In addition, MC1R can modify the risk of melanoma in individuals with mutation in the CDKN2A gene. The CDKN2A gene is involved in regulating the progression of the cell cycle and one of the key known factors for inherited susceptibility to melanoma. This study seeks to evaluate the role of SLC45A2 variant rs250417, which is common in Mediterranean populations, in the presence of MC1R gene variants as modifying factors for the development of melanoma in CDKN2A mutation carriers from Mediterranean countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><center><h3>Tissue Study</h3></center></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The MelaNostrum Consortium will conduct a molecular classification project using formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE) tissue samples collected from primary melanoma tumors, re-excision from areas around the tumor, and metastatic site tissue. Whole genome methylation profiling and sequencing  will be conducted on the DNA extracted from these tissues to explore the determinants of melanoma progression.  </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em>Tissue study projects: </em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Pilot study - Examination of methylation levels in primary tumors and metastatic lesions from melanoma patients </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact: Mario Maldala\'</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>DNA extraction and methylation (chemical \"tags\" that modulate gene expression) profiling from FFPE (formalin-fixed, paraffin embedded) melanoma tumor and surrounding tissue can present challenges, including DNA degradation (fragmentation) from FFPE preservation and oxidation of DNA by melanin. Therefore, a pilot study is being conducted to test the feasibility of measuring whole gneome methylation levels in DNA from FFPE samples. The current pilot study is testing the quantity and quality of DNA extracted using different kits and approaches and conducts methylation profiling using the Infinium MethylationEPIC array. The results will inform the protocol and technologies that will be used in a genome-wide methylation study of primary and metastatic melanoma tissues.   </p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','','full_html');
