INSERT INTO `search_dataset` VALUES (3,'node',' research our research casecontrol study the melanostrum casecontrol study consists of melanoma patients recruited from hospitals universities and clinical centers affiliated with consortium members from italy spain greece and cyprus along with controls recruited at each site clinical and phenotypic information such as number of melanocytic nevi moles and freckles skin type hair and eye color and sunburns as well as environmental exposures were collected by clinical examination interviews and or selfreport data and biospecimens collected from participants of this study will be used to investigate melanoma risk and progression associated with genetic phenotypic and environmental factors casecontrol study projects  genomewide association study gwas  contact maria teresa landi genomewide association studies gwas have identified several genetic variants mainly in proximity of genes that are related to pigmentation nevus mole density dna repair or telomere maintenance that are associated with melanoma risk gwas studies of melanoma risk however have included few individuals of mediterranean descent this casecontrol study will compare genetic variants among melanoma patients from mediterranean countries to healthy people from the general populations of those countries and then combine the results with results from other populations to investigate the common and different pathways leading to melanoma development next generation sequencing for characterization of nonacral sporadic cutaneous melanoma unrelated to common risk factors contact eduardo nagore most cutaneous melanomas develop through patterns of either sun sensitivity ie fair pigmentation of skin and hair and chronic sun damage or melanocytic nevi moles and intermittent sun exposure however a small percentage of nonacral melanomas are unrelated to common known risk factors it is thought these nonacral melanomas are associated with susceptibility genes unrelated to pigmentation or neviproneness the goals of this study are to identify and characterize nonacral melanomas that are not associated to chronic sun damage neviproneness or other common risk factors and understand if these melanomas have distinct clinical behaviors and prognoses targeted sequencing will be performed on dna extracted from tumors of patients with and without common risk factors the results will be used to classify melanomas based on specific mutation profiles and to compare survival between different disease types the findings can be of great clinical importance because melanomas that develop in the absence of common risk factors tend to be asymptomatic and occur at young ages analysis of phenotypic characteristics sun exposure and genetic variants in southern europe northern europe and australia contact maria teresa landi melanocytic nevus mole count has a strong genetic component for individuals with many nevi melanoma risk is only moderately associated with sun exposure alternatively melanoma risk among individuals with few or no nevi is strongly associated with patterns of sun exposure complicating these risk patterns are pigmentation phenotypes fair vs dark which also have strong genetic components pigmentation is associated with sun sensitivity and may also influence an individual s sun exposure behaviors in this study three populations that differ in pigmentation and sun intensity southern europe dark pigmentation intense sun northern europe fair pigmentation moderate sun and australia fair pigmentation intense sun will be investigated to better understand the complex patterns of association between phenotypic characteristics genetic variants and melanoma risk sun exposure intensity and pattern has been assessed via selfreport and or satellite measurement of uva uvb radiation and measurement of chronic sun damage in the area adjacent to melanoma lesions additional molecular and genomics analyses will be conducted in the future imputation of hlaregion and association with melanoma risk and response to treatment contact maria teresa landi the hla system human leukocyte antigen plays an essential role in immune system function proteins in one part of this system display peptides from inside a cell onto the surface of the cell where they can be identified by tcells of the immune system tcells recognize and bind to foreign or nonself peptides which initiates a process that causes cell death the role of hla in the recognition of abnormal cells by the immune system may be important for cancer risk and treatment in this study the hla gene region will be genotyped and imputed or directly sequenced from dna extracted from the healthy tissue of melanoma patients that have undergone immunotherapy hla data will be used to investigate possible associations between hla variants and responses to immunotherapy which includes survival melanoma progression changes in tumor size metastasis and recurrences family study individuals with two or more 1st degree relatives with a history of melanoma are at greater risk of developing melanoma than the general population only a portion of these familial melanomas are attributable to the heritable genetic risks that have been identified todate or risk factors shared among close relatives such as pigmentation and sun exposure patterns the melanostrum family study seeks to further understand familial melanoma risk by incorporating sequencing data from mediterranean southern european northern european and australian populations offering an opportunity to study familial melanoma risk across different populations family study projects  whole exome sequencing to identify rare or rare and common variants and melanoma risk in familial settings contact maria teresa landi a portion of familial melanoma risk is hereditary in nature a few susceptibility genes have already been identified including cdkn2a and cdk4 both of which have a role in cell cycle progression collaborative research involving members of melanostrum have recently identified a rare variant in the protection of telomeres 1 pot1 as a high susceptibility gene the variant arose as a founder mutation in the area of romagna italy wholeexome sequencing sequencing of the protein coding regions of dna in melanomaprone families excluding those with known mutations such as cdkn2a and cdk4 will be performed to continue investigating rare and or common genetic variants associated with melanoma risk in a familial setting effects of immunity on the development of melanoma in families where genetic and environmental factors are similar contact maria teresa landi there tends to be a high degree of similarity among family members with respect to common known melanoma risk factors including skin type and sun exposure patterns this presents an opportunity to investigate how variation in other factors such as immunity may affect the development of melanoma associations between melanoma development and immunological markers measured in blood will be investigated atm mutations in melanoma susceptibility contact paola ghiorzo atm is a gene that plays an important role in dna repair consequently atm is associated with predisposition to certain cancers genomewide association studies gwas have established atm as a low penetrance melanoma susceptibility gene and population studies have linked specific atm genetic variants with increased melanoma risk to better understand the role of atm in melanoma susceptibility this study will evaluate atm gene variants observed in melanomaprone families atm data will be collected from melanomaprone families unrelated melanoma patients and diseasefree individuals the number of loss of function inactivation and missense amino acid substitution atm variants in melanomaprone family members and melanoma patients will be identified and compared to diseasefree controls evaluation of ccdc83 as a candidate melanoma susceptibility gene contact susana puig the ccdc83 gene has been found to be expressed to a much higher degree in several cancers than in normal healthy tissue mutations of ccdc83 have also been observed in several tumors including melanomas although the specific function of the gene has not been well established genome analyses of melanomaprone families have identified variants of ccdc83 as one of the likely discriminators between family members that develop melanoma and those that do not these observations provide a rationale for assessing the possible role of ccdc83 in melanoma susceptibility this study will investigate the association between ccdc83 and melanoma by comparing the prevalence of loss of function inactivation and missense amino acid substitution ccdc83 variants identified in melanomaprone families to families not prone to developing melanoma evaluation of slc45a2 variant rs250417 and mc1r variants as modifying factors for the development of melanoma in cdkn2a mutation carriers from mediterranean countries contact susana puig fair skin and hair and sun sensitivity are known risk factors for melanoma development the master regulator of pigmentation is the gene melanocortin1 receptor mc1r when activated it leads to the production of eumelanin brown black dark pigmentation the gene slc45a2 also influences pigmentation by playing a role in melanin synthesis genetic variations in both these genes have been linked to increased risk of melanoma in addition mc1r can modify the risk of melanoma in individuals with mutation in the cdkn2a gene the cdkn2a gene is involved in regulating the progression of the cell cycle and one of the key known factors for inherited susceptibility to melanoma this study seeks to evaluate the role of slc45a2 variant rs250417 which is common in mediterranean populations in the presence of mc1r gene variants as modifying factors for the development of melanoma in cdkn2a mutation carriers from mediterranean countries tissue study the melanostrum consortium will conduct a molecular classification project using formalinfixed paraffinembedded ffpe tissue samples collected from primary melanoma tumors reexcision from areas around the tumor and metastatic site tissue whole genome methylation profiling and sequencing will be conducted on the dna extracted from these tissues to explore the determinants of melanoma progression tissue study projects  pilot study examination of methylation levels in primary tumors and metastatic lesions from melanoma patients contact mario maldala  dna extraction and methylation chemical tags that modulate gene expression profiling from ffpe formalinfixed paraffin embedded melanoma tumor and surrounding tissue can present challenges including dna degradation fragmentation from ffpe preservation and oxidation of dna by melanin therefore a pilot study is being conducted to test the feasibility of measuring whole gneome methylation levels in dna from ffpe samples the current pilot study is testing the quantity and quality of dna extracted using different kits and approaches and conducts methylation profiling using the infinium methylationepic array the results will inform the protocol and technologies that will be used in a genomewide methylation study of primary and metastatic melanoma tissues  ',0);
